\\subsection{Stacks and queues}
\\label{sec:stacks-queues}

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.9\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_2.jpeg}
\\caption{An array implementation of a stack $S$. Stack elements appear only in the lightly shaded positions. (a) Stack $S$ has 4 elements. The top element is 9. (b) Stack $S$ after the calls $\\text{PUSH}(S, 17)$ and $\\text{PUSH}(S, 3)$. (c) Stack $S$ after the call $\\text{POP}(S)$ has returned the element 3, which is the one most recently pushed. Although element 3 still appears in the array, it is no longer in the stack; the top is element 17.}
\\label{fig:stack-array}
\\end{figure}

inserted element. The stack consists of elements $S[1 \\ldots S.\\text{top}]$, where $S[1]$ is the element at the bottom of the stack and $S[S.\\text{top}]$ is the element at the top.

When $S.\\text{top} = 0$, the stack contains no elements and is \\textit{empty}. We can test to see whether the stack is empty by query operation \\textsc{Stack-Empty}. If we attempt to pop an empty stack, we say the stack \\textit{underflows}, which is normally an error. If $S.\\text{top}$ exceeds $n$, the stack \\textit{overflows}. (In our pseudocode implementation, we don't worry about stack overflow.)

We can implement each of the stack operations with just a few lines of code:

\\begin{algorithm}
\\textsc{Stack-Empty}($S$) \\\\
\\quad 1 \\textbf{if} $S.\\text{top} == 0$ \\\\
\\quad \\quad \\textbf{return} \\textsc{True} \\\\
\\quad 2 \\textbf{else} \\textbf{return} \\textsc{False}

\\textsc{Push}($S, x$) \\\\
\\quad 1 $S.\\text{top} = S.\\text{top} + 1$ \\\\
\\quad 2 $S[S.\\text{top}] = x$

\\textsc{Pop}($S$) \\\\
\\quad 1 \\textbf{if} \\textsc{Stack-Empty}($S$) \\\\
\\quad \\quad \\textbf{error} ``underflow'' \\\\
\\quad 2 \\textbf{else} $S.\\text{top} = S.\\text{top} - 1$ \\\\
\\quad 3 \\textbf{return} $S[S.\\text{top} + 1]$
\\end{algorithm}

Figure~\\ref{fig:stack-array} shows the effects of the modifying operations \\textsc{Push} and \\textsc{Pop}. Each of the three stack operations takes $O(1)$ time.

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_2.jpeg}
\\caption{A queue implemented using an array $Q[1 \\ldots 12]$. Queue elements appear only in the lightly shaded positions. (a) The queue has 5 elements, in locations $Q[7 \\ldots 11]$. (b) The configuration of the queue after the calls $\\text{ENQUEUE}(Q, 17)$, $\\text{ENQUEUE}(Q, 3)$, and $\\text{ENQUEUE}(Q, 5)$. (c) The configuration of the queue after the call $\\text{DEQUEUE}(Q)$ returns the key value 15 formerly at the head of the queue. The new head has key 6.}
\\label{fig:queue}
\\end{figure}

\\section{Queues}

We call the INSERT operation on a queue ENQUEUE, and we call the DELETE operation DEQUEUE; like the stack operation POP, DEQUEUE takes no element argument. The FIFO property of a queue causes it to operate like a line of customers waiting to pay a cashier. The queue has a \\textit{head} and a \\textit{tail}. When an element is enqueued, it takes its place at the tail of the queue, just as a newly arriving customer takes a place at the end of the line. The element dequeued is always the one at the head of the queue, like the customer at the head of the line who has waited the longest.

Figure~\\ref{fig:queue} shows one way to implement a queue of at most $n - 1$ elements using an array $Q[1 \\ldots n]$. The queue has an attribute $Q.\\text{head}$ that indexes, or points to, its head. The attribute $Q.\\text{tail}$ indexes the next location at which a newly arriving element will be inserted into the queue. The elements in the queue reside in locations $Q.\\text{head}, Q.\\text{head} + 1, \\ldots, Q.\\text{tail} - 1$, where we ``wrap around'' in the sense that location 1 immediately follows location $n$ in a circular order. When $Q.\\text{head} = Q.\\text{tail}$, the queue is empty. Initially, we have $Q.\\text{head} = Q.\\text{tail} = 1$. If we attempt to dequeue an element from an empty queue, the queue underflows.

\\subsection{Searching a linked list}
The procedure \\textsc{List-Search}(L, k) finds the first element with key $k$ in list $L$ by a simple linear search, returning a pointer to this element. If no object with key $k$ appears in the list, then the procedure returns \\textsc{nil}. For the linked list in Figure 10.3(a), the call \\textsc{List-Search}(L, 4) returns a pointer to the third element, and the call \\textsc{List-Search}(L, 7) returns \\textsc{nil}.

\\begin{algorithm}
\\textsc{List-Search}(L, k) \\\\
1\\quad $x = L.\\text{head}$ \\\\
2\\quad \\textbf{while} $x \\neq \\text{nil}$ and $x.\\text{key} \\neq k$ \\\\
3\\quad\\quad $x = x.\\text{next}$ \\\\
4\\quad \\textbf{return} $x$
\\end{algorithm}

To search a list of $n$ objects, the \\textsc{List-Search} procedure takes $\\Theta(n)$ time in the worst case, since it may have to search the entire list.

\\subsection{Inserting into a linked list}
Given an element $x$ whose key attribute has already been set, the \\textsc{List-Insert} procedure ``splices'' $x$ onto the front of the linked list, as shown in Figure 10.3(b).

