\\includegraphics[width=0.5\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_2.jpeg}
\\caption{A treap. Each node $x$ is labeled with $x.\\text{key} : x.\\text{priority}$. For example, the root has key $G$ and priority 4.}
\\label{fig:treap}
\\end{figure}

We will examine a data structure that answers this question in the affirmative. A \\textit{treap} is a binary search tree with a modified way of ordering the nodes. Figure~\\ref{fig:treap} shows an example. As usual, each node $x$ in the tree has a key value $x.\\text{key}$. In addition, we assign $x.\\text{priority}$, which is a random number chosen independently for each node. We assume that all priorities are distinct and also that all keys are distinct. The nodes of the treap are ordered so that the keys obey the binary-search-tree property and the priorities obey the min-heap order property:

\\begin{itemize}
    \\item If $v$ is a left child of $u$, then $v.\\text{key} < u.\\text{key}$.
    \\item If $v$ is a right child of $u$, then $v.\\text{key} > u.\\text{key}$.
    \\item If $v$ is a child of $u$, then $v.\\text{priority} > u.\\text{priority}$.
\\end{itemize}

(This combination of properties is why the tree is called a ``treap'': it has features of both a binary search tree and a heap.)

It helps to think of treaps in the following way. Suppose that we insert nodes $x_1, x_2, \\dots, x_n$, with associated keys, into a treap. Then the resulting treap is the tree that would have been formed if the nodes had been inserted into a normal binary search tree in the order given by their (randomly chosen) priorities, i.e., $x_i.\\text{priority} < x_j.\\text{priority}$ means that we had inserted $x_i$ before $x_j$.

\\begin{itemize}
    \\item \\textit{a.} Show that given a set of nodes $x_1, x_2, \\dots, x_n$, with associated keys and priorities, all distinct, the treap associated with these nodes is unique.
    \\item \\textit{b.} Show that the expected height of a treap is $\\Theta(\\lg n)$, and hence the expected time to search for a value in the treap is $\\Theta(\\lg n)$.
\\end{itemize}

Let us see how to insert a new node into an existing treap. The first thing we do is assign to the new node a random priority. Then we call the insertion algorithm, which we call \\textsc{Treap-Insert}, whose operation is illustrated in Figure~\\ref{fig:treap-insert}.

