for $i = 1, 2, \\ldots, n-1$. We denote a decomposition into pieces using ordinary additive notation, so that $7 = 2 + 2 + 3$ indicates that a rod of length 7 is cut into three pieces---two of length 2 and one of length 3. If an optimal solution cuts the rod into $k$ pieces, for some $1 \\le k \\le n$, then an optimal decomposition
\\[
n = i_1 + i_2 + \\cdots + i_k
\\]
of the rod into pieces of lengths $i_1, i_2, \\ldots, i_k$ provides maximum corresponding revenue
\\[
r_n = p_{i_1} + p_{i_2} + \\cdots + p_{i_k}.
\\]

For our sample problem, we can determine the optimal revenue figures $r_i$, for $i = 1, 2, \\ldots, 10$, by inspection, with the corresponding optimal decompositions

\\footnotetext{
If we required the pieces to be cut in order of nondecreasing size, there would be fewer ways to consider. For $n = 4$, we would consider only 5 such ways: parts (a), (b), (c), (e), and (h) in Figure~\\ref{fig:rod-cutting-ways}. The number of ways is called the \\emph{partition function}; it is approximately equal to $e^{\\pi\\sqrt{2n/3}}/4n\\sqrt{3}$. This quantity is less than $2^{n-1}$, but still much greater than any polynomial in $n$. We shall not pursue this line of inquiry further, however.
}

