Figure~\\ref{fig:17.3} plots the values of $num_i$, $size_i$, and $\\Phi_i$ against $i$. Notice how the potential builds to pay for expanding the table.

\\subsection{17.4.2 Table expansion and contraction}

To implement a TABLE-DELETE operation, it is simple enough to remove the specified item from the table. In order to limit the amount of wasted space, however, we might wish to \\emph{contract} the table when the load factor becomes too small. Table contraction is analogous to table expansion: when the number of items in the table drops too low, we allocate a new, smaller table and then copy the items from the old table into the new one. We can then free the storage for the old table by returning it to the memory-management system. Ideally, we would like to preserve two properties:

\\begin{itemize}
    \\item the load factor of the dynamic table is bounded below by a positive constant, and
    \\item the amortized cost of a table operation is bounded above by a constant.
\\end{itemize}

