\\begin{algorithm}[htbp]
\\caption{B-TREE-SPLIT-CHILD($x, i$)}
\\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\\STATE $z = \\text{ALLOCATE-NODE}()$
\\STATE $y = x.c_i$
\\STATE $z.\\text{leaf} = y.\\text{leaf}$
\\STATE $z.n = t - 1$
\\FOR{$j = 1$ to $t - 1$}
\\STATE $z.key_j = y.key_{j+t}$
\\ENDFOR
\\IF{not $y.\\text{leaf}$}
\\FOR{$j = 1$ to $t$}
\\STATE $z.c_j = y.c_{j+t}$
\\ENDFOR
\\ENDIF
\\STATE $y.n = t - 1$
\\FOR{$j = x.n + 1$ downto $i + 1$}
\\STATE $x.c_{j+1} = x.c_j$
\\ENDFOR
\\STATE $x.c_{i+1} = z$
\\FOR{$j = x.n$ downto $i$}
\\STATE $x.key_{j+1} = x.key_j$
\\ENDFOR
\\STATE $x.key_i = y.key_t$
\\STATE $x.n = x.n + 1$
\\STATE $\\text{DISK-WRITE}(y)$
\\STATE $\\text{DISK-WRITE}(z)$
\\STATE $\\text{DISK-WRITE}(x)$
\\end{algorithmic}
\\end{algorithm}

B-TREE-SPLIT-CHILD works by straightforward ``cutting and pasting.'' Here, $x$ is the node being split, and $y$ is $x$'s $i$th child (set in line 2). Node $y$ originally has $2t$ children ($2t - 1$ keys) but is reduced to $t$ children ($t - 1$ keys) by this operation. Node $z$ takes the $t$ largest children ($t - 1$ keys) from $y$, and $z$ becomes a new child

