\\subsection{20.2.1 Proto van Emde Boas structures}

Taking our cue from recurrence (20.2), let us design a recursive data structure to support the operations. Although this data structure will fail to achieve our goal of $O(\\lg \\lg u)$ time for some operations, it serves as a basis for the van Emde Boas tree structure that we will see in Section 20.3.

For the universe $\\{0, 1, 2, \\dots, u-1\\}$, we define a \\textbf{proto van Emde Boas structure}, or \\textbf{proto-vEB structure}, which we denote as \\texttt{proto-vEB}(u), recursively as follows. Each \\texttt{proto-vEB}(u) structure contains an attribute $u$ giving its universe size. In addition, it contains the following:

\\begin{itemize}
    \\item If $u = 2$, then it is the base size, and it contains an array $A[0..1]$ of two bits.
    \\item Otherwise, $u = 2^{2^k}$ for some integer $k \\ge 1$, so that $u \\ge 4$. In addition to the universe size $u$, the data structure \\texttt{proto-vEB}(u) contains the following attributes, illustrated in Figure~\\ref{fig:proto-vEB}:
    \\begin{itemize}
        \\item a pointer named \\texttt{summary} to a \\texttt{proto-vEB}($\\sqrt{u}$) structure and
        \\item an array \\texttt{cluster}[$0 \\dots \\sqrt{u} - 1$] of $\\sqrt{u}$ pointers, each to a \\texttt{proto-vEB}($\\sqrt{u}$) structure.
    \\end{itemize}
\\end{itemize}

The element $x$, where $0 \\le x < u$, is recursively stored in the cluster numbered $\\text{high}(x)$ as element $\\text{low}(x)$ within that cluster.

In the two-level structure of the previous section, each node stores a summary array of size $\\sqrt{u}$, in which each entry contains a bit. From the index of each entry, we can compute the starting index of the subarray of size $\\sqrt{u}$ that the bit summarizes. In the proto-vEB structure, we use explicit pointers rather than index

