\\subsection{20.3.1 van Emde Boas trees}

The \\emph{van Emde Boas tree}, or \\emph{vEB tree}, modifies the proto-vEB structure. We denote a vEB tree with a universe size of $u$ as $vEB(u)$ and, unless $u$ equals the base size of 2, the attribute \\emph{summary} points to a $vEB(\\sqrt[4]{u})$ tree and the array $cluster[0 \\dots \\sqrt[4]{u}-1]$ points to $\\sqrt[4]{u}$ $vEB(\\sqrt[4]{u})$ trees. As Figure~\\ref{fig:20.5} illustrates, a vEB tree contains two attributes not found in a proto-vEB structure:
\\begin{itemize}
    \\item \\emph{min} stores the minimum element in the vEB tree, and
    \\item \\emph{max} stores the maximum element in the vEB tree.
\\end{itemize}
Furthermore, the element stored in \\emph{min} does not appear in any of the recursive $vEB(\\sqrt[4]{u})$ trees that the \\emph{cluster} array points to. The elements stored in a $vEB(u)$ tree $V$, therefore, are $V.\\text{min}$ plus all the elements recursively stored in the $vEB(\\sqrt[4]{u})$ trees pointed to by $V.\\text{cluster}[0 \\dots \\sqrt[4]{u}-1]$. Note that when a vEB tree contains two or more elements, we treat \\emph{min} and \\emph{max} differently: the element

