\\subsection{Disjoint-set forests}
\\label{sec:disjoint-sets}

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_2.jpeg}
\\caption{A disjoint-set forest. (a) Two trees representing the two sets of Figure 21.2. The tree on the left represents the set $\\{b, c, e, h\\}$, with $c$ as the representative, and the tree on the right represents the set $\\{d, f, g\\}$, with $f$ as the representative. (b) The result of $\\textsc{Union}(e, g)$.}
\\label{fig:disjoint-sets-forest}
\\end{figure}

We perform the three disjoint-set operations as follows. A $\\textsc{Make-Set}$ operation simply creates a tree with just one node. We perform a $\\textsc{Find-Set}$ operation by following parent pointers until we find the root of the tree. The nodes visited on this simple path toward the root constitute the \\emph{find path}. A $\\textsc{Union}$ operation, shown in Figure~\\ref{fig:disjoint-sets-forest}(b), causes the root of one tree to point to the root of the other.

\\subsubsection{Heuristics to improve the running time}

So far, we have not improved on the linked-list implementation. A sequence of $n - 1$ $\\textsc{Union}$ operations may create a tree that is just a linear chain of $n$ nodes. By using two heuristics, however, we can achieve a running time that is almost linear in the total number of operations $m$.

The first heuristic, \\emph{union by rank}, is similar to the weighted-union heuristic we used with the linked-list representation. The obvious approach would be to make the root of the tree with fewer nodes point to the root of the tree with more nodes. Rather than explicitly keeping track of the size of the subtree rooted at each node, we shall use an approach that eases the analysis. For each node, we maintain a \\emph{rank}, which is an upper bound on the height of the node. In union by rank, we make the root with smaller rank point to the root with larger rank during a $\\textsc{Union}$ operation.

The second heuristic, \\emph{path compression}, is also quite simple and highly effective. As shown in Figure~\\ref{fig:path-compression}, we use it during $\\textsc{Find-Set}$ operations to make each node on the find path point directly to the root. Path compression does not change any ranks.

