pants). A directed edge $(u, v)$ in the dag of Figure~\\ref{fig:topological-sort}(a) indicates that garment $u$ must be donned before garment $v$. A topological sort of this dag therefore gives an order for getting dressed. Figure~\\ref{fig:topological-sort}(b) shows the topologically sorted dag as an ordering of vertices along a horizontal line such that all directed edges go from left to right.

The following simple algorithm topologically sorts a dag:

\\begin{algorithm}
\\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\\STATE \\textsc{TOPOLOGICAL-SORT}(G)
\\STATE call \\textsc{DFS}(G) to compute finishing times $v.f$ for each vertex $v$
\\STATE as each vertex is finished, insert it onto the front of a linked list
\\STATE \\textbf{return} the linked list of vertices
\\end{algorithmic}
\\end{algorithm}

Figure~\\ref{fig:topological-sort}(b) shows how the topologically sorted vertices appear in reverse order of their finishing times.

We can perform a topological sort in time $\\Theta(V + E)$, since depth-first search takes $\\Theta(V + E)$ time and it takes $O(1)$ time to insert each of the $|V|$ vertices onto the front of the linked list.

We prove the correctness of this algorithm using the following key lemma characterizing directed acyclic graphs.

