\\section{Relaxation}

The algorithms in this chapter use the technique of \\emph{relaxation}. For each vertex $v \\in V$, we maintain an attribute $v.d$, which is an upper bound on the weight of a shortest path from source $s$ to $v$. We call $v.d$ a \\emph{shortest-path estimate}. We initialize the shortest-path estimates and predecessors by the following $\\Theta(V)$-time procedure:

\\begin{algorithm}
\\textsc{Initialize-Single-Source}$(G, s)$
\\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\\For{each vertex $v \\in G.V$}
\\State $v.d = \\infty$
\\State $v.\\pi = \\text{NIL}$
\\EndFor
\\State $s.d = 0$
\\end{algorithmic}
\\end{algorithm}

After initialization, we have $v.\\pi = \\text{NIL}$ for all $v \\in V$, $s.d = 0$, and $v.d = \\infty$ for $v \\in V - \\{s\\}$.

The process of \\emph{relaxing} an edge $(u, v)$ consists of testing whether we can improve the shortest path to $v$ found so far by going through $u$ and, if so, updating $v.d$ and $v.\\pi$. A relaxation step\\footnote{It may seem strange that the term ``relaxation'' is used for an operation that tightens an upper bound. The use of the term is historical. The outcome of a relaxation step can be viewed as a relaxation of the constraint $v.d \\le u.d + w(u, v)$, which, by the triangle inequality (Lemma~\\ref{lem:24.10}), must be satisfied if $u.d = \\delta(s, u)$ and $v.d = \\delta(s, v)$. That is, if $v.d \\le u.d + w(u, v)$, there is no ``pressure'' to satisfy this constraint, so the constraint is ``relaxed.'' } may decrease the value of the shortest-path

\\end{document}

