\\subsection*{Lemma 24.2}
Let $G = (V, E)$ be a weighted, directed graph with source $s$ and weight function $w : E \\to \\mathbb{R}$, and assume that $G$ contains no negative-weight cycles that are reachable from $s$. Then, after the $|V|-1$ iterations of the \\textbf{for} loop of lines 2--4 of Bellman-Ford, we have $v.d = \\delta(s, v)$ for all vertices $v$ that are reachable from $s$.

\\textbf{Proof} We prove the lemma by appealing to the path-relaxation property. Consider any vertex $v$ that is reachable from $s$, and let $p = \\langle v_0, v_1, \\ldots, v_k \\rangle$, where $v_0 = s$ and $v_k = v$, be any shortest path from $s$ to $v$. Because shortest paths are simple, $p$ has at most $|V|-1$ edges, and so $k \\leq |V|-1$. Each of the $|V|-1$ iterations of the \\textbf{for} loop of lines 2--4 relaxes all $|E|$ edges. Among the edges relaxed in the $i$th iteration, for $i = 1, 2, \\ldots, k$, is $(v_{i-1}, v_i)$. By the path-relaxation property, therefore, $v.d = v_k.d = \\delta(s, v_k) = \\delta(s, v)$.

