\\subsection*{Theorem 24.5}
If a weighted, directed graph $G = (V, E)$ has source vertex $s$ and no cycles, then at the termination of the \\textsc{DAG-SHORTEST-PATHS} procedure, $v.d = \\delta(s, v)$ for all vertices $v \\in V$, and the predecessor subgraph $G_{\\pi}$ is a shortest-paths tree.

\\textbf{Proof} We first show that $v.d = \\delta(s, v)$ for all vertices $v \\in V$ at termination. If $v$ is not reachable from $s$, then $v.d = \\delta(s, v) = \\infty$ by the no-path property. Now, suppose that $v$ is reachable from $s$, so that there is a shortest path $p = \\langle v_0, v_1, \\ldots, v_k \\rangle$, where $v_0 = s$ and $v_k = v$. Because we pro-

