When the capacities are integral and the optimal flow value $|f^*|$ is small, the running time of the Ford-Fulkerson algorithm is good. Figure 26.7(a) shows an example of what can happen on a simple flow network for which $|f^*|$ is large. A maximum flow in this network has value 2,000,000: 1,000,000 units of flow traverse the path $s \\to u \\to t$, and another 1,000,000 units traverse the path $s \\to v \\to t$. If the first augmenting path found by \\textsc{Ford-Fulkerson} is $s \\to u \\to v \\to t$, shown in Figure 26.7(a), the flow has value 1 after the first iteration. The resulting residual network appears in Figure 26.7(b). If the second iteration finds the augmenting path $s \\to v \\to u \\to t$, as shown in Figure 26.7(b), the flow then has value 2. Figure 26.7(c) shows the resulting residual network. We can continue, choosing the augmenting path $s \\to v \\to u \\to t$ in the odd-numbered iterations and the augmenting path $s \\to v \\to u \\to t$ in the even-numbered iterations. We would perform a total of 2,000,000 augmentations, increasing the flow value by only 1 unit in each.

