\\section{The Edmonds-Karp algorithm}

We can improve the bound on \\textsc{FORD-FULKERSON} by finding the augmenting path $p$ in line 3 with a breadth-first search. That is, we choose the augmenting path as a \\emph{shortest} path from $s$ to $t$ in the residual network, where each edge has unit distance (weight). We call the Ford-Fulkerson method so implemented the \\emph{Edmonds-Karp algorithm}. We now prove that the Edmonds-Karp algorithm runs in $O(VE^2)$ time.

The analysis depends on the distances to vertices in the residual network $G_f$. The following lemma uses the notation $\\delta_f(u, v)$ for the shortest-path distance from $u$ to $v$ in $G_f$, where each edge has unit distance.

\\begin{lemma}
If the Edmonds-Karp algorithm is run on a flow network $G = (V, E)$ with source $s$ and sink $t$, then for all vertices $v \\in V - \\{s, t\\}$, the shortest-path distance $\\delta_f(s, v)$ in the residual network $G_f$ increases monotonically with each flow augmentation.
\\end{lemma}

\\end{document}

\\documentclass{article}
\\usepackage{graphicx}
\\usepackage{amsmath}
\\usepackage{amssymb}

\\begin{document}

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.9\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_2.jpeg}
\\caption{(a) A flow network for which FORD-FULKERSON can take $\\Theta(E |f^*|)$ time, where $f^*$ is a maximum flow, shown here with $|f^*| = 2,000,000$. The shaded path is an augmenting path with residual capacity 1. (b) The resulting residual network, with another augmenting path whose residual capacity is 1. (c) The resulting residual network.}
\\label{fig:26.7}
\\end{figure}

\\textbf{Proof} We will suppose that for some vertex $v \\in V - \\{s, t\\}$, there is a flow augmentation that causes the shortest-path distance from $s$ to $v$ to decrease, and then we will derive a contradiction. Let $f$ be the flow just before the first augmentation that decreases some shortest-path distance, and let $f'$ be the flow just afterward. Let $v$ be the vertex with the minimum $\\delta_{f'}(s,v)$ whose distance was decreased by the augmentation, so that $\\delta_{f'}(s,v) < \\delta_f(s,v)$. Let $p = s \\rightsquigarrow u \\rightarrow v$ be a shortest path from $s$ to $v$ in $G_{f'}$, so that $(u,v) \\in E_{f'}$ and
\\begin{equation}
\\delta_{f'}(s, u) = \\delta_{f'}(s, v) - 1. \\tag{26.12}
\\end{equation}
Because of how we chose $v$, we know that the distance of vertex $u$ from the source $s$ did not decrease, i.e.,
\\begin{equation}
\\delta_{f'}(s, u) \\ge \\delta_f(s, u). \\tag{26.13}
\\end{equation}
We claim that $(u, v) \\notin E_f$. Why? If we had $(u, v) \\in E_f$, then we would also have
\\begin{align*}
\\delta_f(s, v) &\\le \\delta_f(s, u) + 1 \\quad \\text{(by Lemma 24.10, the triangle inequality)} \\\\
&\\le \\delta_{f'}(s, u) + 1 \\quad \\text{(by inequality (26.13))} \\\\
&= \\delta_{f'}(s, v) \\quad \\text{(by equation (26.12))},
\\end{align*}
which contradicts our assumption that $\\delta_{f'}(s, v) < \\delta_f(s, v)$.

How can we have $(u, v) \\notin E_f$ and $(u, v) \\in E_{f'}$? The augmentation must have increased the flow from $v$ to $u$. The Edmonds-Karp algorithm always augments flow along shortest paths, and therefore it augmented along a shortest path from $s$ to $u$ in $G_f$ that has $(v, u)$ as its last edge. Therefore,
\\begin{align*}
\\delta_f(s, v) &= \\delta_f(s, u) - 1 \\\\
&\\le \\delta_{f'}(s, u) - 1 \\quad \\text{(by inequality (26.13))} \\\\
&= \\delta_{f'}(s, v) - 2 \\quad \\text{(by equation (26.12))}.
\\end{align*}

