\\subsection*{Minimum-cost flow}

We are given a directed graph $G = (V, E)$ in which each edge $(u, v) \\in E$ has a nonnegative capacity $c(u, v) \\ge 0$. As in the maximum-flow problem, we implicitly assume that $c(u, v) = 0$ for $(u, v) \\notin E$, and that the graph has no antiparallel edges. We are also given a source vertex $s$ and a sink vertex $t$, and a desired flow value $d$. The goal is to find a flow $f$ of value $d$ from $s$ to $t$ that minimizes the total cost, where the cost of sending one unit of flow along edge $(u, v)$ is $a(u, v)$. We denote the flow on edge $(u, v)$ by $f_{uv}$.

The problem is to find a flow $f$ that satisfies the following constraints: the value of the flow is exactly $d$ units, and with the new objective function of minimizing the cost:
\\begin{equation}
\\minimize \\sum_{(u,v)\\in E} a(u,v) f_{uv}
\\tag{29.51}
\\end{equation}
subject to
\\begin{align}
f_{uv} &\\leq c(u,v) \\quad \\text{for each } u,v\\in V, \\\\
\\sum_{v\\in V} f_{vu} - \\sum_{v\\in V} f_{uv} &= 0 \\quad \\text{for each } u\\in V-\\{s,t\\}, \\\\
\\sum_{v\\in V} f_{sv} - \\sum_{v\\in V} f_{vs} &= d, \\\\
f_{uv} &\\geq 0 \\quad \\text{for each } u,v\\in V.
\\tag{29.52}
\\end{align}

\\subsection*{Multicommodity flow}

As a final example, we consider another flow problem. Suppose that the Lucky Puck company from Section 26.1 decides to diversify its product line and ship not only hockey pucks, but also hockey sticks and hockey helmets. Each piece of equipment is manufactured in its own factory, has its own warehouse, and must be shipped, each day, from factory to warehouse. The sticks are manufactured in Vancouver and must be shipped to Saskatoon, and the helmets are manufactured in Edmonton and must be shipped to Regina. The capacity of the shipping network does not change, however, and the different items, or \\textit{commodities}, must share the same network.

This example is an instance of a \\textbf{multicommodity-flow problem}. In this problem, we are again given a directed graph $G = (V, E)$ in which each edge $(u, v) \\in E$ has a nonnegative capacity $c(u, v) \\ge 0$. As in the maximum-flow problem, we implicitly assume that $c(u, v) = 0$ for $(u, v) \\notin E$, and that the graph has no antiparallel edges.

