In a public-key cryptosystem, encryption works as shown in Figure~\\ref{fig:31.5}. Suppose Bob wishes to send Alice a message $M$ encrypted so that it will look like unintelligible gibberish to an eavesdropper. The scenario for sending the message goes as follows.

\\begin{itemize}
\\item Bob obtains Alice's public key $P_A$ (from a public directory or directly from Alice).
\\item Bob computes the \\textit{ciphertext} $C = P_A(M)$ corresponding to the message $M$ and sends $C$ to Alice.
\\item When Alice receives the ciphertext $C$, she applies her secret key $S_A$ to retrieve the original message: $S_A(C) = S_A(P_A(M)) = M$.
\\end{itemize}

Because $S_A()$ and $P_A()$ are inverse functions, Alice can compute $M$ from $C$. Because only Alice is able to compute $S_A()$, Alice is the only one who can compute $M$ from $C$. Because Bob encrypts $M$ using $P_A()$, only Alice can understand the transmitted message.

We can just as easily implement digital signatures within our formulation of a public-key cryptosystem. (There are other ways of approaching the problem of constructing digital signatures, but we shall not go into them here.) Suppose now that Alice wishes to send Bob a digitally signed response $M'$. Figure~\\ref{fig:31.6} shows how the digital-signature scenario proceeds.

\\begin{itemize}
\\item Alice computes her \\textit{digital signature} $\\sigma$ for the message $M'$ using her secret key $S_A$ and the equation $\\sigma = S_A(M')$.
\\end{itemize}

