\\section{32.3 String matching with finite automata}

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.5\\textwidth]{_page_0_Picture_2.jpeg}
\\caption{An illustration for the proof of Lemma 32.2. The figure shows that $r \\le \\sigma(x) + 1$, where $r = \\sigma(xa)$.}
\\label{fig:32.8}
\\end{figure}

To clarify the operation of a string-matching automaton, we now give a simple, efficient program for simulating the behavior of such an automaton (represented by its transition function $\\delta$) in finding occurrences of a pattern $P$ of length $m$ in an input text $T[1..n]$. As for any string-matching automaton for a pattern of length $m$, the state set $Q$ is $\\{0, 1, \\ldots, m\\}$, the start state is 0, and the only accepting state is state $m$.

\\begin{algorithm}[H]
\\caption{FINITE-AUTOMATON-MATCHER $(T, \\delta, m)$}
\\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\\STATE $n = T.length$
\\STATE $q = 0$
\\FOR{$i = 1$ to $n$}
\\STATE $q = \\delta(q, T[i])$
\\IF{$q = m$}
\\STATE print ``Pattern occurs with shift'' $i - m$
\\ENDIF
\\ENDFOR
\\end{algorithmic}
\\end{algorithm}

From the simple loop structure of FINITE-AUTOMATON-MATCHER, we can easily see that its matching time on a text string of length $n$ is $\\Theta(n)$. This matching time, however, does not include the preprocessing time required to compute the transition function $\\delta$. We address this problem later, after first proving that the procedure FINITE-AUTOMATON-MATCHER operates correctly.

Consider how the automaton operates on an input text $T[1..n]$. We shall prove that the automaton is in state $\\sigma(T_i)$ after scanning character $T[i]$. Since $\\sigma(T_i) = m$ if and only if $P \\sqsupset T_i$, the machine is in the accepting state $m$ if and only if it has just scanned the pattern $P$. To prove this result, we make use of the following two lemmas about the suffix function $\\sigma$.

\\begin{lemma}[Suffix-function inequality]
For any string $x$ and character $a$, we have $\\sigma(xa) \\le \\sigma(x) + 1$.
\\end{lemma}

\\begin{proof}
Referring to Figure~\\ref{fig:32.8}, let $r = \\sigma(xa)$. If $r = 0$, then the conclusion $\\sigma(xa) = r \\le \\sigma(x) + 1$ is trivially satisfied, by the nonnegativity of $\\sigma(x)$. Now assume that $r > 0$. Then, $P_r \\sqsupset xa$, by the definition of $\\sigma$. Thus, $P_{r-1} \\sqsupset x$, by

