The pseudocode below gives the Knuth-Morris-Pratt matching algorithm as the procedure \\textsc{KMP-Matcher}. For the most part, the procedure follows from \\textsc{Finite-Automaton-Matcher}, as we shall see. \\textsc{KMP-Matcher} calls the auxiliary procedure \\textsc{Compute-Prefix-Function} to compute $\\pi$.

\\begin{algorithm}[H]
\\caption{\\textsc{KMP-Matcher}$(T, P)$}
\\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\\STATE $n = T.\\text{length}$
\\STATE $m = P.\\text{length}$
\\STATE $\\pi = \\textsc{Compute-Prefix-Function}(P)$
\\STATE $q = 0$ \\COMMENT{number of characters matched}
\\FOR{$i = 1$ to $n$} \\COMMENT{scan the text from left to right}
    \\WHILE{$q > 0$ and $P[q + 1] \\neq T[i]$}
        \\STATE $q = \\pi[q]$ \\COMMENT{next character does not match}
    \\ENDWHILE
    \\IF{$P[q + 1] == T[i]$}
        \\STATE $q = q + 1$ \\COMMENT{next character matches}
    \\ENDIF
    \\IF{$q == m$}
        \\STATE print ``Pattern occurs with shift'' $i - m$ \\COMMENT{is all of $P$ matched?}
        \\STATE $q = \\pi[q]$ \\COMMENT{look for the next match}
    \\ENDIF
\\ENDFOR
\\end{algorithmic}
\\end{algorithm}

