Many definitions for directed and undirected graphs are the same, although certain terms have slightly different meanings in the two contexts. If $(u, v)$ is an edge in a directed graph $G = (V, E)$, we say that $(u, v)$ is \\textbf{incident from} or \\textbf{leaves} vertex $u$ and is \\textbf{incident to} or \\textbf{enters} vertex $v$. For example, the edges leaving vertex 2 in Figure B.2(a) are $(2, 2)$, $(2, 4)$, and $(2, 5)$. The edges entering vertex 2 are $(1, 2)$ and $(2, 2)$. If $(u, v)$ is an edge in an undirected graph $G = (V, E)$, we say that $(u, v)$ is \\textbf{incident on} vertices $u$ and $v$. In Figure B.2(b), the edges incident on vertex 2 are $(1, 2)$ and $(2, 5)$.

If $(u, v)$ is an edge in a graph $G = (V, E)$, we say that vertex $v$ is \\textit{adjacent} to vertex $u$. When the graph is undirected, the adjacency relation is symmetric. When the graph is directed, the adjacency relation is not necessarily symmetric. If $v$ is adjacent to $u$ in a directed graph, we sometimes write $u \\to v$. In parts (a) and (b) of Figure B.2, vertex 2 is adjacent to vertex 1, since the edge $(1, 2)$ belongs to both graphs. Vertex 1 is \\textit{not} adjacent to vertex 2 in Figure B.2(a), since the edge $(2, 1)$ does not belong to the graph.

The \\textit{degree} of a vertex in an undirected graph is the number of edges incident on it. For example, vertex 2 in Figure B.2(b) has degree 2. A vertex whose degree is 0, such as vertex 4 in Figure B.2(b), is \\textit{isolated}. In a directed graph, the \\textit{out-degree} of a vertex is the number of edges leaving it, and the \\textit{in-degree} of a vertex is the number of edges entering it. The \\textit{degree} of a vertex in a directed graph is its in-

